The '''Dnieper River''' (also known as: ''Dnepr'', ''Dniapro'', or ''Dnipro'') is a [[river]] which flows from [[Russia]], through [[Belarus]] and [[Ukraine]], ending its flow in the [[Black Sea]]. Its total length is 2,285 [[kilometer|km]], of which 485 km lie within Russia, 595 km within Belarus, and 1,095 km within Ukraine. The Dnieper's Basin covers 504,000 [[square kilometer|km<U+00B2>]], of which 289,000 km<U+00B2> are within the territory of Ukraine.<ref name="EoU">{{cite web|url=http://www.encyclopediaofukraine.com/display.asp?AddButton=pages\D\N\DnieperRiver.htm |title=Dnieper River |accessdate= |accessmonthday=January 19 |accessyear=2007 |author= |last=[[Volodymyr Kubiyovych|Kubiyovych]] |first=Volodymyr |authorlink= |coauthors=Ivan Teslia |work=Encyclopedia of Ukraine |language=English }}</ref>

The Dnieper finds its source in the [[Valdai Hills]] of central Russia, at an elevation of 220 [[Metre|m]], among turf swamps.<ref name="EoU">{{cite web|url=http://www.encyclopediaofukraine.com/display.asp?AddButton=pages\D\N\DnieperRiver.htm |title=Dnieper River |accessdate= |accessmonthday=January 19 |accessyear=2007 |author= |last=[[Volodymyr Kubiyovych|Kubiyovych]] |first=Volodymyr |authorlink= |coauthors=Ivan Teslia |work=Encyclopedia of Ukraine |language=English }}</ref> It later runs south eventually flowing into the [[Black Sea]]. 115 kilometres of its length serve as a natural border between Belarus and Ukraine. Approximately the last 800 kilometres of the river is a chain of nearly consecutive reservoirs.

The Dnieper is connected with the [[Western Bug]] by the [[Dnieper-Bug Canal]]. Its estuary, or [[Liman (landform)|liman]], used to be defended by the strong fortress of [[Ochakiv]].

